Didn't realize thread was nearly ded, reposting quick review of Into the Wildlands to make sure the bloke sees it

Very nice stuff, love the premise, the characters, the content included. Acknowledging how fast things were moving time-wise in the story was a good idea, actually heightened my suspension of disbelief by letting me think "OK, at least they're aware how quick all this drama's unfolding and they're not all on board with it". The dream sequence was handled in an interesting and enjoyable way, but I feel like changing scene so often made it hard for me to keep up.
With regards to critique, I only have two complaints.
A: You very occasionally shift perspective without distinguishing it in any way, such as during the fight in chapter 12 where you describe things Colton is thinking, feeling or trying to achieve when Erik couldn't know them.
B: The first chapter sets a much more humourous tone than the rest of the more dramatic story, which is not so bad in and of itself but it does feel like it shifts focus a little too suddenly. That said, the jokes you used were funny, I won't lie
Having said all that I'm really looking forward to seeing more of your story. I want to see what happens next for the main characters, and the town around them, and see how/if their lives improve. The word comfy's kinda lost it's meaning a bit but I actually feel it applies here, it'll be nice to just see more, you got me invested in the characters and the setting

>>53058306
It doesn't surprise me in the slightest that Niven was OK with interspecies romance in a work in his setting, given that the second Ringworld book revolved almost completely around the concept of Rishatra. That is, formalized interspecies sex between homonids that is the equivalent of a handshake. I'm pretty sure the Kzin whips his dick out at some point.

Look at that, I found a conversation about Niven from 2000, and Sternberg is part of it. He says the following:
>Well, I've had the good fortune to sit on a couch opposite Mr. Niven while he slobbered all over my barely-covered-in-leather wife. And he never knew I was there, or who I was, which is good considering that I'm the guy he flames in the intro to MKzW4.

Sternberg was and probably still is active in the Seattle BDSM scene, so that explains the leather. This seems to be a bit of a rabbit hole, but it can be said conclusively that this isn't just a simple case of an author taking umbrage at a random story. Niven clearly knew who Sternberg was, and Sternberg was and is a prolific erotica author some of whom's work was clearly derivative of Ringworld. He's still active online, and like any true, old curmudgeon maintains his own ancient-looking site: https://pendorwright.com/

My verdict for now: It was personal.

>>53061869
That's not what I expected, but I'm not surprised.

This is a scan of an image from a book printed in the 70s, with Niven's blessing. This is what the Kzinti look like, according to him. Adult males are 8-9 feet tall and weigh around a third of a ton, and evolved on a planet where surface gravity was almost double what it is on Earth. Humans find them fugly and goofy-looking, which makes certain aspects of their behavior and culture all the more shocking and alarming to the humans who have to deal with them in-setting.

But, and perhaps I am misremembering, the story to which Niven objected specifically was called "The Kittenin," which you can find if you really want to, but I found the contents sufficiently unsettling that I am reluctant to put a link here. It was a short vignette of quasi-incest between a human and his adopted daughter, a Kzin ("Kzinti" is the plural). And she's underage. It managed to creep me right the fuck out, and I frequent /trash/.

And the autistic pedantry lobe of my brains says many aspects of it are so wrong for Niven's setting and species that I wonder if it was originally written as a creepy story of a human and a cute shy catgirl, then altered just slightly in order to tweak Niven's nose. The Kzinti genetically engineered themselves to make themselves more like their gods when they learned how. They altered their species radically. Males made themselves instinctively hyperaggressive, because that's how their gods were. Kzinti females, at the "present" of Niven's stories in the "Known Space" setting, are non-sapient animals the males keep around as a highly alarming combination of pets, zoo animals, and breeding stock. Ing's story involves an isolated group of pre-genetic-engineered Kzinti placed on an isolated world many thousands of years before by godlike aliens, and they aren't nearly the assholes that most of their species are. Their females are still cute shy catgirls, though.

Another annoying bit. This image is from the 1970s animated Star Trek. They got permission to adapt one of Niven's stories, and put the Kzinti, and a number of other setting-breaking things from Known Space, canonically into the Star Trek 'verse. The artists managed to draw them looking at least recognizable, in the sense that they have vaguely feline features and articulated ears with thin bones running through them, and they like combinations of colors that make a human's brain hurt, though they aren't nearly as big as the originals, and they are neither silly-looking enough nor ugly enough. >>53062855
You are misremembering, because the offending story is The Only Fair Game, which is about Kzinti males being prison BDSM gay due to their unfortunate relationship with the species' females. Both are on the site I linked, BTW. I found someone who asked Niven about it directly, and apparently Niven answered that he was told it violated his copyright. So either he's being formal, or it really was just a case of Old Man Yells At Cloud because his lawyers told him to. But Sternberg definitely took it personally.

As for the look of the Kzinti, I tend not to put much stock in "official" art, especially for older stuff. I remember Discworld only getting good covers because of the old artist kicking the bucket, and he was one of those older artists who just did whatever. You could sort of tell which character was supposed to be which, but that was it. Then Pratchett got the new artist, and he actually drew stuff that looked like he'd read the books in question and listened to the writer. Semi-predictably, then they also started doing more visual content. Either way, the official Kzinti basket skeleton looks like it wouldn't provide much dexterity. The Kzin were also present in Star Trek The Animated Series, and there they appear more human-like, and that's also Niven-approved canon. Of course, they also dress in pink because someone got the colors wrong. And apparently one appeared on Lower Decks as well, so the Kzin are still part of Trek. Weird.

To be entirely fair to Niven, an aspect of copyright law in the US is that if someone else uses your copyrighted characters, or whatever, and you fail to take legal action to defend the copyright, some courts will hold that you're turning them over to the public domain by choosing not to act. And then there is the stuff about "parody" and "fair use," and it's too complicated for me to grasp. I am not a lawyer and all the big words slide off my small, smooth little brain.

Also, once upon a time, sci-fi publishing houses would go to random artists and say "paint us something science fictiony. It can be as weird and surreal as you want, or realistic. We're not picky, we don't really care, and we won't pay you very much." There were exceptions. Frank Kelly Freas was brilliant and it usually seemed like he'd read the stories. But usually the editor would end up holding a picture of a giant metal skull with a window in the side of it, with bars on it, and a guy looking through the bars, and flames behind him. And he'd hand it to one of his publication's authors and say "Write a story about this."

Hey it's AP, been a hot minute since I posted a chapter update. Just wanted to let those who like Vipers, Nights, and French Fries know, I'm basically taking a short break to work on a different story. Been working on slice of life viper stories for a year and a half, and I wanted to mix it up. Had a bunch of ideas for dragon stories floating around in my head and I wanted to get a couple concept chapters for an idea down on "paper". Almost done with 1st chapter, will probably post it tomorrow or Sunday.

I'm calling it: Of Crimson Scales. Story takes place during ~860AD (after the Carolingian empire was divided up). Concept is the son of the duke of Swabia(MC) is diplomatically being taken as a hostage by a dragoness to use as leverage to prevent humans from moving into her hunting grounds/territory. I've put a lot of thought into the setting (it's still a work in progress), taking inspiration from biblical lore and folk lore. Currently there's only humans, dragons, Nephilim(giants), and cynocephali(dog headed people) living in the world. There's no magic, humans develop siege equipment to deal with the dragons. Too many details to list on one post, but feel free to ask questions if you have any.
